{"kind":"Article","sha256":"f692ed1de6bcc5c4c6259ff44f270292396f06a6553c6358506544124b0d384a","slug":"blog.2018.kinds-of-openness","location":"/blog/2018/kinds-of-openness.md","dependencies":[],"frontmatter":{"title":"How do projects signal how “open” they are?","tags":["open source","governance","community"],"date":"2018-10-26","content_includes_title":false,"authors":[{"id":"chris","nameParsed":{"literal":"Chris Holdgraf","given":"Chris","family":"Holdgraf"},"name":"Chris Holdgraf","orcid":"0000-0002-2391-0678","affiliations":["affiliations-myst-generated-uid-0","affiliations-myst-generated-uid-1"],"twitter":"choldgraf","github":"choldgraf","url":"https://chrisholdgraf.com"}],"github":"https://github.com/choldgraf/choldgraf.github.io","affiliations":[{"name":"2i2c","url":"https://2i2c.org","id":"affiliations-myst-generated-uid-0"},{"name":"Project Jupyter","url":"https://jupyter.org","id":"affiliations-myst-generated-uid-1"}],"exports":[{"format":"md","filename":"kinds-of-openness.md","url":"/build/kinds-of-openness-e8d6175294a6cb784f84860777988f3c.md"}]},"mdast":{"type":"root","children":[{"type":"block","children":[{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":13,"column":1},"end":{"line":16,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"How do open projects signal their “openness” to the outside community? This is\na really hard question, particularly because nowadays “open” has become a buzzword\nthat doesn’t just signal a project’s position to the community, but is also used\nas a marketing term to increase support, users, or resources.","position":{"start":{"line":13,"column":1},"end":{"line":13,"column":1}},"key":"sgKeSssNBo"}],"key":"TXUA1h1z5f"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":18,"column":1},"end":{"line":18,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"I was thinking about this the other day, so decided to take to twitter:","position":{"start":{"line":18,"column":1},"end":{"line":18,"column":1}},"key":"JgoNL4mfrc"}],"key":"HYL8Bx9r6u"},{"type":"link","url":"https://twitter.com/choldgraf/status/1054478362209480704","children":[{"type":"text","value":"https://​twitter​.com​/choldgraf​/status​/1054478362209480704","key":"ziAulkYBL1"}],"urlSource":"https://twitter.com/choldgraf/status/1054478362209480704","key":"tBugAmIL1n"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":23,"column":1},"end":{"line":24,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"I was surprised at how much this question resonated with people. Here are a few\nhighlights from the (very interesting) conversation that came out of that question.","position":{"start":{"line":23,"column":1},"end":{"line":23,"column":1}},"key":"HRM49NiqXn"}],"key":"sTUs8dpFci"},{"type":"heading","depth":2,"position":{"start":{"line":26,"column":1},"end":{"line":26,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Some discussion threads","position":{"start":{"line":26,"column":1},"end":{"line":26,"column":1}},"key":"vOxcj1iRXE"}],"identifier":"some-discussion-threads","label":"Some discussion threads","html_id":"some-discussion-threads","implicit":true,"key":"qKyLXAVNJu"},{"type":"heading","depth":3,"position":{"start":{"line":28,"column":1},"end":{"line":28,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Wishes vs. reality","position":{"start":{"line":28,"column":1},"end":{"line":28,"column":1}},"key":"Fzsg2tlrJO"}],"identifier":"wishes-vs-reality","label":"Wishes vs. reality","html_id":"wishes-vs-reality","implicit":true,"key":"ZBzFv8bIAY"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":30,"column":1},"end":{"line":31,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Tal immediately brought up a really important point: many projects ","position":{"start":{"line":30,"column":1},"end":{"line":30,"column":1}},"key":"nDiLMuaWum"},{"type":"emphasis","position":{"start":{"line":30,"column":1},"end":{"line":30,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"want","position":{"start":{"line":30,"column":1},"end":{"line":30,"column":1}},"key":"G5O2Mlc5Yl"}],"key":"bAtnfHZZTf"},{"type":"text","value":" to be\ninclusive and welcoming to others, but they don’t have time to do so.","position":{"start":{"line":30,"column":1},"end":{"line":30,"column":1}},"key":"kySyw06M3U"}],"key":"dEzZQYNdz4"},{"type":"link","url":"https://twitter.com/talyarkoni/status/1054484496769314818","children":[{"type":"text","value":"https://​twitter​.com​/talyarkoni​/status​/1054484496769314818","key":"mFCgYtx9n7"}],"urlSource":"https://twitter.com/talyarkoni/status/1054484496769314818","key":"ZoQMquae54"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":36,"column":1},"end":{"line":39,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"I think this is an important distinction, and something that should be signaled\nclearly. One the one hand, if a person generally wants others to contribute to\nthe project, then they’re some degree of openness higher than a project that\nactively discourages this.","position":{"start":{"line":36,"column":1},"end":{"line":36,"column":1}},"key":"pKSMitYCAQ"}],"key":"zKRptEfI7x"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":41,"column":1},"end":{"line":47,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"On the other hand, running open projects ","position":{"start":{"line":41,"column":1},"end":{"line":41,"column":1}},"key":"DQ647nzhFl"},{"type":"emphasis","position":{"start":{"line":41,"column":1},"end":{"line":41,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"does take work","position":{"start":{"line":41,"column":1},"end":{"line":41,"column":1}},"key":"O7xKnctWTv"}],"key":"EuCQ2MNlCL"},{"type":"text","value":",\nand a project that says “well I’d like to be open but can’t commit the time to do it”\nalso isn’t ","position":{"start":{"line":41,"column":1},"end":{"line":41,"column":1}},"key":"zX6EnwETs5"},{"type":"emphasis","position":{"start":{"line":41,"column":1},"end":{"line":41,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"that","position":{"start":{"line":41,"column":1},"end":{"line":41,"column":1}},"key":"tA8jcIzuJm"}],"key":"LGREpsL2PN"},{"type":"text","value":" open in practice. No hard feelings there, but I think that\nthe goal of defining a “degree of openness” isn’t to signal a value judgment on the\npeople related to the project, but on the project itself. If you really want to\ngrow an open community around a project, you need to dedicate time and resources to\nthe community itself, not just the technical pieces of the tool.","position":{"start":{"line":41,"column":1},"end":{"line":41,"column":1}},"key":"kR4vODZK4x"}],"key":"ye2kCr0r0v"},{"type":"heading","depth":2,"position":{"start":{"line":49,"column":1},"end":{"line":49,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Metrics of openness","position":{"start":{"line":49,"column":1},"end":{"line":49,"column":1}},"key":"bfKjSZ4m0o"}],"identifier":"metrics-of-openness","label":"Metrics of openness","html_id":"metrics-of-openness","implicit":true,"key":"WdBrUgLiFR"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":51,"column":1},"end":{"line":53,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"That leaves open the question: “how do we measure the ","position":{"start":{"line":51,"column":1},"end":{"line":51,"column":1}},"key":"MNESLZQyi8"},{"type":"strong","position":{"start":{"line":51,"column":1},"end":{"line":51,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"practical","position":{"start":{"line":51,"column":1},"end":{"line":51,"column":1}},"key":"t18vkNfV7I"}],"key":"BpOzoWqr1V"},{"type":"text","value":" openness of a project,\nrather than just what it ","position":{"start":{"line":51,"column":1},"end":{"line":51,"column":1}},"key":"BgHZa8rpIN"},{"type":"strong","position":{"start":{"line":51,"column":1},"end":{"line":51,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"says","position":{"start":{"line":51,"column":1},"end":{"line":51,"column":1}},"key":"XhpsDY0AvN"}],"key":"O7Xg1TV4aM"},{"type":"text","value":"?”. A few folks mentioned that the CHAOSS project\ndoes a lot of work in this gneeral space:","position":{"start":{"line":51,"column":1},"end":{"line":51,"column":1}},"key":"WlfcLi0G3L"}],"key":"rv2ULtCPtj"},{"type":"link","url":"https://twitter.com/abbycabs/status/1054492219808403457","children":[{"type":"text","value":"https://​twitter​.com​/abbycabs​/status​/1054492219808403457","key":"QUrVYEqpqe"}],"urlSource":"https://twitter.com/abbycabs/status/1054492219808403457","key":"LqWRoVwiTu"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":58,"column":1},"end":{"line":60,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"CHAOSS defines standards for metrics to collect about communities. They don’t necessarily\nsay what others should ","position":{"start":{"line":58,"column":1},"end":{"line":58,"column":1}},"key":"sIp2ArTRYV"},{"type":"strong","position":{"start":{"line":58,"column":1},"end":{"line":58,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"do","position":{"start":{"line":58,"column":1},"end":{"line":58,"column":1}},"key":"YGp0PChlG3"}],"key":"nHg9hv81HH"},{"type":"text","value":" with those metrics, so perhaps that’s on the open community\nto define for themselves.","position":{"start":{"line":58,"column":1},"end":{"line":58,"column":1}},"key":"o1uDRaOmBV"}],"key":"WSZDjTdPsC"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":62,"column":1},"end":{"line":63,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Personally, I’d love to see more tooling that makes it possible to scrape activity\nstatistics from open repositories. Tal and others suggested a few things:","position":{"start":{"line":62,"column":1},"end":{"line":62,"column":1}},"key":"pYtAQqZ0lo"}],"key":"zs5GYvITlv"},{"type":"list","ordered":false,"spread":false,"position":{"start":{"line":65,"column":1},"end":{"line":70,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":65,"column":1},"end":{"line":65,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"time to initial response to new issues (maybe separated by new vs. old contributors)","position":{"start":{"line":65,"column":1},"end":{"line":65,"column":1}},"key":"BcR3wXT8dh"}],"key":"ZYWMqZwibO"},{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":66,"column":1},"end":{"line":66,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"inequality coefficient for contributor commits","position":{"start":{"line":66,"column":1},"end":{"line":66,"column":1}},"key":"ztNkv2ABtc"}],"key":"ksdGVDX2qB"},{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":67,"column":1},"end":{"line":67,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"number of unique organizations/email domains in contrbutors","position":{"start":{"line":67,"column":1},"end":{"line":67,"column":1}},"key":"Ghdw56iJlw"}],"key":"nywV2BnoCI"},{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":68,"column":1},"end":{"line":68,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"use of positive/welcoming language","position":{"start":{"line":68,"column":1},"end":{"line":68,"column":1}},"key":"v153Q0ENwG"}],"key":"MDagNuQ9Sb"},{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":69,"column":1},"end":{"line":70,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"explicit roles defined, and pathways towards working more with the community","position":{"start":{"line":69,"column":1},"end":{"line":69,"column":1}},"key":"jc27Ak9VHM"}],"key":"BS8HRYTYqr"}],"key":"Rp7xD3G4so"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":71,"column":1},"end":{"line":73,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"I’d love to see more thoughts along these lines. If we could define a collection of\nmetrics around openness, it’d paint a much more rich picture than simply “does this\nproject have a permissive license.”","position":{"start":{"line":71,"column":1},"end":{"line":71,"column":1}},"key":"xkeSLmqund"}],"key":"er0y4cjCzn"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":75,"column":1},"end":{"line":75,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"There was also a specific metric around governance that’s worth highlighting:","position":{"start":{"line":75,"column":1},"end":{"line":75,"column":1}},"key":"tPzuBla6IM"}],"key":"j0UfGzgSm1"},{"type":"link","url":"https://twitter.com/GeorgLink/status/1054621070945329152","children":[{"type":"text","value":"https://​twitter​.com​/GeorgLink​/status​/1054621070945329152","key":"LS9Ub7xkgC"}],"urlSource":"https://twitter.com/GeorgLink/status/1054621070945329152","key":"OAbR74beKU"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":80,"column":1},"end":{"line":84,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"The paper linked above is a study that investigated “open governance” in a number of\nopen-source mobile projects. It’s an interesting exploration of the ways that\ndecision-making is made (and signaled) in several projects. Perhaps unsurprisingly, they\nconclude that “more open” projects are most-likely to be successful in the long term\n(with a few exceptions).","position":{"start":{"line":80,"column":1},"end":{"line":80,"column":1}},"key":"WASXkfzxZW"}],"key":"r493kyhmdC"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":86,"column":1},"end":{"line":87,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Finally, apparently there’s also a “badge” to signal the status of a repository (is it\nactive, vaporware, abandoned, etc):","position":{"start":{"line":86,"column":1},"end":{"line":86,"column":1}},"key":"cYWswoQEJn"}],"key":"yLgXL3pyyk"},{"type":"link","url":"https://twitter.com/parente/status/1055053470808580098","children":[{"type":"text","value":"https://​twitter​.com​/parente​/status​/1055053470808580098","key":"HnK3gUn2Nb"}],"urlSource":"https://twitter.com/parente/status/1055053470808580098","key":"G8Ty1mDLtR"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":92,"column":1},"end":{"line":96,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"I’d love to see more of these semi-automated signals to help guide the open source community\nin deciding what projects to adopt and contribute to. As more and more people do\ntheir work online and in the open, it also creates a challenge of sifting through the noise\nto make the most of your (limited) time and energy. Having better metrics like these will\nmake these decisions easier.","position":{"start":{"line":92,"column":1},"end":{"line":92,"column":1}},"key":"FUvyEAwRKA"}],"key":"UDjVCARpO0"},{"type":"heading","depth":3,"position":{"start":{"line":98,"column":1},"end":{"line":98,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Mozilla’s archetypes of open projects","position":{"start":{"line":98,"column":1},"end":{"line":98,"column":1}},"key":"OB8uZrQ6km"}],"identifier":"mozillas-archetypes-of-open-projects","label":"Mozilla’s archetypes of open projects","html_id":"mozillas-archetypes-of-open-projects","implicit":true,"key":"Np3Basz92v"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":100,"column":1},"end":{"line":101,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"One of the most fascinating links I found was Mozilla’s “archetypes of open projects”\ndocument:","position":{"start":{"line":100,"column":1},"end":{"line":100,"column":1}},"key":"ImO0yesXsT"}],"key":"WAU4TNmJQ1"},{"type":"link","url":"https://twitter.com/neuromusic/status/1054517145436975104","children":[{"type":"text","value":"https://​twitter​.com​/neuromusic​/status​/1054517145436975104","key":"qpzLs95Aa8"}],"urlSource":"https://twitter.com/neuromusic/status/1054517145436975104","key":"LFDU1YS9Gg"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":106,"column":1},"end":{"line":109,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Briefly, this is an internal document that Mozilla made public. It attempts to define\nthe different kinds of open projects that exist. Importantly, it also explains the\nvalue propositions of each, how it can be used strategically within an organization, and\nhow it supports (or doesn’t) an open community around it.","position":{"start":{"line":106,"column":1},"end":{"line":106,"column":1}},"key":"NLeF2HeGQN"}],"key":"PMF4Xf8k8w"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":111,"column":1},"end":{"line":115,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"I added some thoughts about how Project Jupyter fits into these archetypes on the\n","position":{"start":{"line":111,"column":1},"end":{"line":111,"column":1}},"key":"OtQgpErRC3"},{"type":"link","url":"https://github.com/jupyter/governance/issues/60#issuecomment-432766439","position":{"start":{"line":111,"column":1},"end":{"line":111,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Jupyter governance research issue","position":{"start":{"line":111,"column":1},"end":{"line":111,"column":1}},"key":"qNCBbkTxWA"}],"urlSource":"https://github.com/jupyter/governance/issues/60#issuecomment-432766439","data":{"kind":"issue","org":"jupyter","repo":"governance","issue_number":"60"},"internal":false,"protocol":"github","key":"miAl6NCMTN"},{"type":"text","value":"\nand I’d love to think more about how these archetypes fit into the pre-existing open communities\nthat are out there. If anybody wants to brainstorm how these archetypes fit into the scientific\nopen community, I’d love to chat :-)","position":{"start":{"line":111,"column":1},"end":{"line":111,"column":1}},"key":"bm7S1tPs0Q"}],"key":"UtREMvzUK7"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":117,"column":1},"end":{"line":119,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"On that note, I want to give a brief shout-out to Mozilla in general, which has\neither conducted or sponsored a bunch of interesting work in open projects.\nFor example, they have a whole wiki dedicated to working openly:","position":{"start":{"line":117,"column":1},"end":{"line":117,"column":1}},"key":"VBURu35Xe2"}],"key":"lkNxQwSxfe"},{"type":"link","url":"https://twitter.com/alex__morley/status/1054483982040121344","children":[{"type":"text","value":"https://​twitter​.com​/alex​_​_morley​/status​/1054483982040121344","key":"GjOg9Ou2JS"}],"urlSource":"https://twitter.com/alex__morley/status/1054483982040121344","key":"UXyL7ebMiy"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":124,"column":1},"end":{"line":126,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"and they also run lots of training and community programs such as the\n","position":{"start":{"line":124,"column":1},"end":{"line":124,"column":1}},"key":"Xbx4kbX2yD"},{"type":"link","url":"https://foundation.mozilla.org/opportunity/mozilla-open-leaders/","position":{"start":{"line":124,"column":1},"end":{"line":124,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Mozilla Open Leaders","position":{"start":{"line":124,"column":1},"end":{"line":124,"column":1}},"key":"rNzP464IZq"}],"urlSource":"https://foundation.mozilla.org/opportunity/mozilla-open-leaders/","key":"NFaSvCI6Hk"},{"type":"text","value":" program.\nProject Jupyter is in this year’s cohort and ","position":{"start":{"line":124,"column":1},"end":{"line":124,"column":1}},"key":"KQSzWLSbve"},{"type":"link","url":"https://github.com/jupyter/governance/issues/57","position":{"start":{"line":124,"column":1},"end":{"line":124,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"keeping track of its progress here","position":{"start":{"line":124,"column":1},"end":{"line":124,"column":1}},"key":"mEiQ7duocY"}],"urlSource":"https://github.com/jupyter/governance/issues/57","data":{"kind":"issue","org":"jupyter","repo":"governance","issue_number":"57"},"internal":false,"protocol":"github","key":"fMttj5Muqr"},{"type":"text","value":".","position":{"start":{"line":124,"column":1},"end":{"line":124,"column":1}},"key":"bL0QGmWlEE"}],"key":"TSTeWs1t4U"},{"type":"heading","depth":3,"position":{"start":{"line":129,"column":1},"end":{"line":129,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Importance of ethnography:","position":{"start":{"line":129,"column":1},"end":{"line":129,"column":1}},"key":"Z7eolwOqrO"}],"identifier":"importance-of-ethnography","label":"Importance of ethnography:","html_id":"importance-of-ethnography","implicit":true,"key":"JFC5Y2AAeY"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":131,"column":1},"end":{"line":131,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"A final note on the importance of ethnography:","position":{"start":{"line":131,"column":1},"end":{"line":131,"column":1}},"key":"kFlL1VULu7"}],"key":"cHexMzwhHv"},{"type":"link","url":"https://twitter.com/mmmpork/status/1054745690897711104","children":[{"type":"text","value":"https://​twitter​.com​/mmmpork​/status​/1054745690897711104","key":"evN5OaJqXM"}],"urlSource":"https://twitter.com/mmmpork/status/1054745690897711104","key":"XGm15awpag"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":136,"column":1},"end":{"line":145,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"For all of my talk about metrics above, I’ve come to appreciate that numbers\nare ","position":{"start":{"line":136,"column":1},"end":{"line":136,"column":1}},"key":"E8JWYDo0bB"},{"type":"strong","position":{"start":{"line":136,"column":1},"end":{"line":136,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"never","position":{"start":{"line":136,"column":1},"end":{"line":136,"column":1}},"key":"UQ27INvkZs"}],"key":"nxV23pDm97"},{"type":"text","value":" sufficient to describe the complexities of a community or group.\nOver the last several years at the ","position":{"start":{"line":136,"column":1},"end":{"line":136,"column":1}},"key":"rVTwebo5U8"},{"type":"link","url":"https://bids.berkeley.edu","position":{"start":{"line":136,"column":1},"end":{"line":136,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Berkeley Institute for Data Science","position":{"start":{"line":136,"column":1},"end":{"line":136,"column":1}},"key":"x5nFVZx5tW"}],"urlSource":"https://bids.berkeley.edu","key":"dKANxqGYGJ"},{"type":"text","value":",\nI’ve had the pleasure of working with several ethnographers who have shared their\nperspective on how to study communities. Semi-automatically-calculated numbers can\nbe a great way to see relatively coarse-level view of a community, but if you really\nwany to understand what’s going on, you need to dig in there, conduct qualitative interviews,\noperate in the community, and create some stories that back up (or not) the quantitative\ndata that you collect. We’d all be better off if there were more ethnographers in our\nrespective communities <3.","position":{"start":{"line":136,"column":1},"end":{"line":136,"column":1}},"key":"gchppmTpMy"}],"key":"uUMJ2G3iPR"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":147,"column":1},"end":{"line":149,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"OK, that’s enough for now - I hope these links are useful and I’ll try to\nupdate them over time if I hear of some new projects along these lines.\nIf you have any suggestions, feel free to leave 'em in the comments!","position":{"start":{"line":147,"column":1},"end":{"line":147,"column":1}},"key":"WC1y8q1Hhm"}],"key":"Qd2zebk6u6"}],"key":"JbLDRPn5js"}],"key":"kNejV1RaDm"},"references":{"cite":{"order":[],"data":{}}},"footer":{"navigation":{"prev":{"title":"Blogging with Jupyter Notebooks and Jekyll using nbconvert templates","url":"/blog/2018/jekyllmarkdown","group":"2018"},"next":{"title":"Introducing makeitpop, a tool to perceptually warp your data!\"","url":"/blog/2018/makeitpop","group":"2018"}}},"domain":"http://localhost:3000"}